3. Source Environment Preparation (VMware vCenter)
3.1 vCenter Service Account Setup

STEP
1	Create Dedicated vCenter Service Account for Nutanix Move
	1. Log in to vCenter as an SSO administrator.
2. Navigate to: Administration → Single Sign On → Users and Groups → Users.
3. Create a new user: move-svc@vsphere.local (or your SSO domain).
4. Assign the following vCenter role permissions at the Datacenter level (propagate to children):

   DATASTORE:  Browse Datastore, Low-Level File Operations, Update VM Files
   NETWORK:    Assign Network
   RESOURCE:   Assign VM to Resource Pool
   VIRTUAL MACHINE → Configuration:  All privileges
   VIRTUAL MACHINE → Snapshot Mgmt:  All privileges (Create, Remove, Revert, Rename)
   VIRTUAL MACHINE → Provisioning:   Allow Disk Access, Allow Read-Only Disk Access
   VIRTUAL MACHINE → Interaction:    Power On, Power Off, Suspend
   GLOBAL:     Cancel Task, Diagnostics
   HOST:       Configuration → Storage Partition Configuration (if direct ESXi access needed)

5. Note the service account credentials securely for Move appliance configuration.

3.2 Enable Changed Block Tracking (CBT) on Source VMs

📋  What is CBT?  Changed Block Tracking (CBT) is a VMware feature that tracks disk blocks changed since the last snapshot. Nutanix Move uses CBT for incremental (delta) sync cycles, dramatically reducing replication time after the initial full copy.

STEP
2	Enable CBT on Source VMs via vCenter
	1. Power off the VM (CBT requires the VM to be powered off for the initial enablement).
   Note: Move can enable CBT automatically if the service account has sufficient privileges.

2. In vCenter, right-click the VM → Edit Settings → VM Options → Advanced → Configuration Parameters.
3. Add or verify these parameters are set:
   ctkEnabled = TRUE
   scsi0:0.ctkEnabled = TRUE   (repeat for each disk: scsi0:1, scsi0:2, etc.)

4. Power the VM back on. Take a snapshot, then delete it — this initialises the CTK files.

5. Alternatively, use PowerCLI to enable CBT in bulk:
   $vm = Get-VM "VM-Name"
   $vm | Get-View | % { $_.ReconfigVM_Task(@{changeVersion=$_.Config.ChangeVersion; extraConfig=@(@{key="ctkEnabled";value="true"})}) }

6. Verify: Right-click VM → Edit Settings → confirm ctkEnabled = true in config params.


3.3 Prepare ESXi Host Access

STEP
3	Validate ESXi Host Connectivity for Move Appliance
	1. Confirm that the Nutanix Move appliance VM (deployed in next section) will have network
   access to all ESXi hosts that host the VMs in scope.
2. Verify VMware NFC (Network File Copy) port TCP 902 is reachable from Move appliance to ESXi hosts.
3. If using vSAN or NFS datastores, confirm Move appliance can reach the storage network.
4. Confirm ESXi hosts are running ESXi 6.0 or later (required by Nutanix Move).
5. Ensure sufficient snapshot space on the datastores hosting source VMs:
   Rule of thumb: Reserve 20-30% additional free space per datastore for snapshot delta files.


 
4. Nutanix Move Appliance — Deployment on vCenter
4.1 Download Nutanix Move OVA

STEP
4	Download Move Appliance from Nutanix Support Portal
	1. Log in to Nutanix Support Portal: https://portal.nutanix.com
2. Navigate to: Downloads → Tools & Firmware → Nutanix Move.
3. Download the latest Move OVA (e.g., move-5.x.x.ova).
4. Verify the SHA-256 checksum of the downloaded OVA against the portal-published hash.
5. Stage the OVA file on a system that has browser/client access to the vCenter web interface.

4.2 Deploy Move Appliance OVA on vCenter

STEP
5	Deploy Move OVA via vCenter Web Client
	1. Log in to vCenter Web Client (https://<vcenter-fqdn>/ui).
2. Right-click the target Cluster or Host → Deploy OVF Template.
3. Select 'Local file' → Upload the Move OVA file.
4. OVF Template Details: Review the summary, click Next.
5. Name & Folder: Set the VM name (e.g., 'Nutanix-Move-Appliance') and choose the target folder.
6. Compute Resource: Select the target ESXi host or cluster.
7. Storage: Select the target datastore — minimum 60 GB required.
   Disk Provisioning: Thin Provision (recommended to save space).
8. Network Mapping: Map the Move appliance's network interface to a port group that has:
   • Access to the vCenter management network
   • Access to all ESXi host management IPs
   • Access to the NC2 cluster (Prism Element IP) — via VPN/Direct Connect
   • Outbound internet access (for Nutanix portal license check — or offline activation)
9. Customise template (OVF Properties):
   • Management IP Address: <static IP for Move appliance>
   • Subnet Mask:           <subnet mask>
   • Default Gateway:       <gateway IP>
   • DNS Server:            <DNS IP>
10. Review the summary and click Finish. Wait for the deployment task to complete (5-10 min).
11. Power ON the Move appliance VM.


📋  Note:  If OVF properties are not available on your vSphere client version, you can configure the IP via the Move VM console after first boot using the set-ip command.

STEP
6	Initial Configuration of Move Appliance
	1. Open a browser and navigate to: https://<Move-Appliance-IP>:8443
2. Accept the self-signed SSL certificate warning.
3. Create the admin password on first login (minimum 8 characters, mixed case + special char).
4. Log in with: Username: admin  |  Password: <set in previous step>
5. (Optional) Configure NTP: Settings → NTP → Add NTP server (e.g., pool.ntp.org or internal NTP).
6. (Optional) Configure syslog/SMTP for alerting under Settings.
7. Verify the Move appliance version is displayed on the dashboard.
8. Check for updates: Settings → Software Upgrade → Check for latest Move release.


 
5. Configure Source (vCenter) in Nutanix Move

STEP
7	Add VMware vCenter as Source Environment in Move
	1. In the Move UI (https://<Move-IP>:8443), click '+ Add Environment'.
2. Select Environment Type: VMware vCenter.
3. Fill in the source details:
   • vCenter IP / FQDN:  <vCenter IP or FQDN>
   • Port:               443 (default)
   • Username:           move-svc@vsphere.local  (service account from Step 1)
   • Password:           <service account password>
4. Click 'Validate'. Move will test API connectivity to vCenter.
5. On successful validation, click 'Add'.
6. The vCenter environment will appear in the Environments list with a green status.
7. Click the vCenter source → Verify that the VM inventory is populated (Datacenter, Clusters, VMs visible).


⚠️  Troubleshooting:  If validation fails — verify TCP 443 is open from the Move appliance to vCenter, and confirm the service account has at least 'Read' access to the root vCenter object.

 
6. Configure Target (NC2 / Nutanix AHV) in Nutanix Move
6.1 NC2 Cluster Preparation

STEP
8	Validate NC2 Cluster Readiness
	1. Log in to Prism Element (https://<NC2-Prism-IP>:9440) using cluster admin credentials.
2. Verify cluster health: Home → Health dashboard — all checks should be green.
3. Confirm available capacity: Hardware → Diagram → verify CPU, memory, and storage headroom.
   Recommended minimum free capacity: 120% of total source VM footprint.
4. Create a dedicated storage container for migrated VMs:
   Storage → Storage Containers → + Storage Container
   Name: e.g., 'Migration-Target-Pool'
   Enable Compression: Yes (recommended for NC2 cloud costs)
   Enable Deduplication: Optional (enable for identical-data workloads)
5. Create or confirm target VM networks exist in Prism:
   Network Configuration → Virtual Networks → confirm VLANs/subnets matching source networks.
6. Create a Nutanix service account for Move:
   Settings (gear icon) → Local User Management → + New User
   Role: Cluster Admin
   Username: move-target-svc

6.2 Add NC2 as Target in Move

STEP
9	Add Nutanix NC2 AHV as Target Environment in Move
	1. In the Move UI, click '+ Add Environment'.
2. Select Environment Type: Nutanix AHV.
3. Fill in the target details:
   • Prism Element IP / FQDN:  <NC2 Prism IP>
   • Port:                     9440 (default)
   • Username:                 move-target-svc
   • Password:                 <service account password>
4. Click 'Validate'. Move will connect to Prism Element API.
5. On successful validation, click 'Add'.
6. The NC2 AHV environment will appear in the Environments list with a green status.
7. Click the NC2 target → verify Storage Containers and Networks are visible.


 
7. Network & Firewall Configuration

STEP
10	Configure Required Firewall Rules
	Open the following ports. Engage the network/security team to apply ACL rules.

  MOVE APPLIANCE → vCENTER:
  TCP 443   – vCenter API (VM inventory, snapshot management)
  TCP 902   – ESXi NFC (Network File Copy) — disk data transfer (agentless mode)

  MOVE APPLIANCE → ESXi HOSTS:
  TCP 902   – NFC replication data channel
  TCP 443   – ESXi management API (if direct host access needed)

  MOVE APPLIANCE → NC2 PRISM:
  TCP 9440  – Prism Element REST API
  TCP 2049  – NFS (if using NFS datastore on NC2 side)

  SOURCE VM → MOVE APPLIANCE (Agent Mode only):
  TCP 8088  – Move Agent communication channel
  TCP 443   – Move appliance HTTPS

  NC2 CVMs (internal, must not be blocked):
  TCP 2074, 2009, 2020 – Nutanix CVM inter-node communication

  GENERAL:
  ICMP (ping) – All nodes to all nodes (health checks)

  After applying rules, validate connectivity:
  From Move appliance console:  nc -zv <vCenter-IP> 443
  From Move appliance console:  nc -zv <NC2-Prism-IP> 9440
  From Move appliance console:  nc -zv <ESXi-Host-IP> 902


Port	Protocol	Source	Destination	Purpose
443	TCP	Move Appliance	vCenter	vCenter REST API
902	TCP	Move Appliance	ESXi Hosts	NFC Disk Replication
9440	TCP	Move Appliance	Nutanix Prism	Prism Element API
8088	TCP	Source VMs	Move Appliance	Move Agent (agent mode)
443	TCP	Source VMs	Move Appliance	Agent HTTPS channel
2049	TCP	Move Appliance	NC2 Storage	NFS (if applicable)
ICMP	—	All	All	Health checks

 
8. Move Agent Installation on Source VMs (Agent-Based Mode)

📋  When is the Agent Required?  The Move Agent is recommended for production VMs to reduce RPO and improve replication throughput. It is mandatory for VMs hosted on non-vCenter managed ESXi hosts or for physical-to-virtual migrations.

8.1 Pre-Agent Installation Checks

STEP
11	Verify Guest OS Compatibility for Move Agent
	Move Agent supports the following operating systems:

  WINDOWS:
  Windows Server 2008 R2, 2012, 2012 R2, 2016, 2019, 2022
  Windows 7, 8.1, 10, 11
  Requires: .NET Framework 4.5+, PowerShell 3.0+, WMI service running

  LINUX:
  RHEL / CentOS 6.x, 7.x, 8.x, 9.x
  Ubuntu 14.04, 16.04, 18.04, 20.04, 22.04
  SLES 11, 12, 15
  Requires: open-vm-tools or VMware Tools installed, systemd or init.d

  Verify the source VM has network connectivity to Move appliance on TCP 8088 and 443.
  Confirm firewall on the guest OS allows inbound TCP 8088 from Move appliance IP.

8.2 Windows VM — Move Agent Installation

STEP
12	Install Move Agent on Windows Source VMs
	1. Download the Move Agent installer from the Move UI:
   Move Dashboard → Source Environment → <vCenter> → Select VM → 'Download Agent'
   Or navigate to: https://<Move-IP>:8443/#/download

2. Copy the installer to the source Windows VM (via RDP, file share, or SCP).

3. On the source Windows VM, run the installer as Administrator:
   Double-click: NutanixMoveAgent_<version>_windows_amd64.msi

4. During installation, enter when prompted:
   Move Appliance IP:   <Move-Appliance-IP>
   Move Appliance Port: 8088

5. Complete the installation wizard. The Move Agent service will start automatically.

6. Verify the agent service is running:
   Services.msc → Look for 'Nutanix Move Agent' → Status: Running
   Or via CMD:  sc query NutanixMoveAgent

7. In the Move UI, confirm the VM now shows agent status as 'Connected'.

8. For bulk deployment across multiple Windows VMs, use one of:
   • Group Policy (GPO) Software Installation
   • SCCM / Intune software deployment
   • PowerShell remoting:  Invoke-Command -ComputerName <VM-list> -ScriptBlock { Start-Process msiexec "/i NutanixMoveAgent.msi /quiet MOVE_IP=<IP> MOVE_PORT=8088" }

8.3 Linux VM — Move Agent Installation

STEP
13	Install Move Agent on Linux Source VMs
	1. Download the Move Agent RPM or DEB package from the Move UI.
   Or use curl/wget from the VM:
   wget https://<Move-IP>:8443/downloads/NutanixMoveAgent_<ver>_linux_amd64.rpm  (for RHEL/CentOS)
   wget https://<Move-IP>:8443/downloads/NutanixMoveAgent_<ver>_linux_amd64.deb  (for Ubuntu/Debian)

   Note: Accept the self-signed cert: wget --no-check-certificate <url>

2. Install the agent:
   RHEL/CentOS:  sudo rpm -ivh NutanixMoveAgent_<ver>_linux_amd64.rpm
   Ubuntu/Debian: sudo dpkg -i NutanixMoveAgent_<ver>_linux_amd64.deb

3. Configure the agent with the Move appliance address:
   sudo /usr/local/nutanix/move-agent/bin/move-agent configure \
     --move-ip <Move-Appliance-IP> --move-port 8088

4. Start and enable the agent service:
   sudo systemctl start move-agent
   sudo systemctl enable move-agent

5. Verify the agent is running:
   sudo systemctl status move-agent
   Expected output: Active: active (running)

6. Check agent connectivity to Move appliance:
   curl -k https://<Move-IP>:8443/api/v1/vms/agent-status

7. In the Move UI, confirm the Linux VM shows agent status as 'Connected'.

8. For bulk deployment on Linux, use Ansible:
   - Copy RPM/DEB to all target VMs
   - Use ansible yum/apt module to install
   - Use ansible systemd module to start and enable the service


 
9. Configure Replication (Migration Plan) in Nutanix Move

STEP
14	Create a Migration Plan in Move
	1. In the Move UI, click '+ Create a Migration Plan'.
2. Plan Name: Enter a descriptive name (e.g., 'Wave1-Production-VMs-Apr2026').
3. Source Environment: Select the vCenter source added in Step 7.
4. Target Environment: Select the NC2 AHV target added in Step 9.
5. Click 'Next'.

6. VM SELECTION:
   Browse the vCenter inventory and select VMs for this migration wave.
   Group by workload type (e.g., web tier, app tier, database tier) for better control.

7. TARGET CONFIGURATION (per VM or bulk):
   • Target Container: Select the storage container created in Step 8 (e.g., 'Migration-Target-Pool')
   • Network Mapping:  Map source vCenter port group → target NC2 network
   • vCPU / RAM:       Retain source values (or right-size if needed)
   • VM Name (Target): Auto-populated from source name; modify if needed

8. REPLICATION SETTINGS:
   • Migration Mode: Agent-based (if agent installed) or Agentless
   • Bandwidth Throttle: Set if needed (e.g., limit to 100 Mbps during business hours)
   • Snapshot Retention: Keep 1 snapshot on source during replication

9. SCHEDULE:
   • Initial Sync: Start immediately or schedule for off-peak hours
   • Delta Sync Interval: Every 1 hour (adjust based on change rate)

10. Review the migration plan summary and click 'Save'.


STEP
15	Start Replication — Initiate Seed Copy
	1. In the Move UI, locate the migration plan created in Step 14.
2. Click 'Start Replication'. Move will perform pre-flight checks:
   ✓ vCenter source connectivity
   ✓ NC2 target connectivity
   ✓ Sufficient storage on target container
   ✓ VM snapshot ability on source
   ✓ Agent connectivity (if agent mode)

3. If pre-flight checks pass, Move will begin the initial SEED COPY (full disk replication).
   This is the longest phase — duration depends on total disk size and available bandwidth.
   Monitor progress: Move UI → Migration Plan → VM list → % Complete

4. Move will automatically take a VMware snapshot on each source VM to begin CBT tracking.
   Source VMs remain powered ON and fully operational during this phase.

5. Upon seed copy completion, Move will automatically switch to INCREMENTAL DELTA SYNC mode.
   Delta syncs will run at the configured interval (e.g., every hour).

6. Monitor the replication health in Move UI:
   • RPO (Recovery Point Objective) — time since last successful delta sync
   • Data lag — outstanding data to be replicated
   • Errors — any VM-level replication failures


✅  Replication Running:  Once VMs show status 'Replicating' with a green indicator in Move and delta syncs are completing successfully, replication is established. Proceed to Part 2 of this runbook for migration execution and post-checks.

 
10. Replication Validation

STEP
16	Validate Replication is Running Successfully
	1. In Move UI, confirm all VMs in the migration plan show status: 'Replicating'.
2. Verify at least one successful delta sync has completed after the initial seed copy.
3. In Prism Element (NC2), navigate to Storage → Storage Containers → confirm data is growing
   in the target container corresponding to replicated VM disk sizes.
4. Check Move event log for any warnings or errors: Move UI → Events / Alerts.
5. Validate network latency and throughput metrics are within expected ranges.
6. Confirm CBT is active on all source VMs: snapshot file (.ctk) exists on source datastore.
7. Optional — perform a TEST CUTOVER on a non-critical VM:
   Move UI → Select VM → Test Cutover
   This powers on a clone of the VM on NC2 in an isolated network for validation.
   The source VM continues running unaffected.
8. Verify the test-cutover VM boots correctly on AHV, VirtIO drivers loaded, network assigns IP.
9. Revert the test cutover after validation: Move UI → Revert Test Cutover.


